            <ce:abstract id="abs0001" view="all" class="author"><ce:abstract-sec id="abss0001" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="spara014" view="all">Reliable tree species diversity and carbon stock data are crucial for establishing a baseline and aiding monitoring and management decision-making to ensure ecosystem functions and services, including carbon management. However, such data are not available for many primary forests, especially in developing countries like Nepal. From this study, we generated primary baseline data on tree species diversity, biomass, and carbon stock for forests under different management regimes in one of the critical landscapes of western Nepal. We sampled 94 clusters of concentric circular sample plots placed systematically at the nodes of 3 km by 3 km square grids in biological corridors (managed by community forest user groups) and a national park's buffer zones (managed by buffer zone user groups) to study the tree species composition and estimate the carbon stock. The number of tree species and botanical families reported in different sites did not differ significantly. The basal area was found to be highest in Brahmadev Corridor where tree density per unit area was also highest. Our study sites showed a basal area ranging from 26.42 to 40.65 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>/ha, which is higher than previously reported from similar forests. The total biomass (302.12 to 496 tons/ha) and carbon stock (142 to 233.12 tons/ha), both being highest in Brahmadev Corridor, were within the range of comparable data and national averages. The number of stems in all sites showed the reverse J-shaped pattern, indicating a stable population and good species recruitment. The buffer zones had a large proportion of forest area with the highest carbon stock classes of 300–400 tons/ha. The basal area and diameter at breast height showed a significant positive correlation with carbon stock, indicating that the basal area is a key determinant of carbon stock. Our study provides disaggregated information on tree species diversity, the quality of forests in terms of stem density and size-class distribution, and carbon stock and its distribution in different carbon stock classes in two forest management regimes. In this sense, our study is the first of its kind in providing important insights into forest and carbon management because areas with different carbon stocks need different management prescriptions.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            
            <ce:keywords id="keys0001" view="all" class="keyword">
               <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0002">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="key0001">
                  <ce:text id="cetext0002">Biodiversity</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0002">
                  <ce:text id="cetext0003">Biological corridor</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0003">
                  <ce:text id="cetext0004">Community forest</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0004">
                  <ce:text id="cetext0005">Forest management</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0005">
                  <ce:text id="cetext0006">Ecosystem service</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="refdata001" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0003">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="para9001" view="all">Data will be made available on request.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec0001" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0004">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="para0002" view="all">Plant diversity affects ecosystem functions and associated ecosystem goods and services (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0011" refid="bib0032">Lange et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0012" refid="bib0036">Liu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Particularly, tree species diversity is regarded as an important component influencing forest productivity and carbon storage at global and local scales (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0013" refid="bib0014">Day et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0014" refid="bib0034">Liang et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). The diversity of tree species has a strong positive relationship with above-ground carbon storage mediated through functional diversity and dominance (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0015" refid="bib0040">Mensah et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Nevertheless, biodiversity and biomass are affected by various factors, including rainfall, climate, soil, and topography as well as human and natural disturbances (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0016" refid="bib0014">Day et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0017" refid="bib0037">Malla et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0018" refid="bib0053">Pragasan, 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0019" refid="bib0068">Timilsina et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0003" view="all">Forests can be both carbon sinks and sources, depending on how they are managed (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0020" refid="bib0052">Pradhan et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0021" refid="bib0036">Liu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0022" refid="bib0018">FAO, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). According to <ce:cross-ref id="crf0023" refid="bib0018">FAO (2020)</ce:cross-ref>, the total carbon stock in forests has decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020, with 44 % stored in living biomass and 45 % in soil organic matter. Tropical forests are a significant reservoir of biodiversity and a source of livelihood. They store about 68 % of global forest carbon stocks, with 45–55 % captured as vegetation biomass and the remaining 10–30 % in the soil, thus, playing a key role in the terrestrial carbon cycle (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0024" refid="bib0046">Pan et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:inter-ref id="interref0001" xlink:href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1470160X23009172#b0120" xlink:type="simple">IPCC, 2019</ce:inter-ref>). The amount of carbon that can be added to the atmosphere or sequestered on land when forests are managed to meet emission targets depends on the quantity of biomass in the forest (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0025" refid="bib0008">Brown et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>). Carbon stock assessment in different ecosystems has attracted wide attention because it helps with understanding the role of different vegetation types in mitigating greenhouse gas and climate change as a part of forest ecosystem services (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0026" refid="bib0012">Chave et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0027" refid="bib0010">Charnley et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0028" refid="bib0031">Kirby and Potvin, 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0029" refid="bib0036">Liu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Further, carbon stock assessment helps monitor and evaluate the effectiveness and integrity of forest-based emissions’ reduction schemes (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0030" refid="bib0047">Pandey et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). The forest type, species composition, and stand age determine the CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> sequestration in the forest (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0031" refid="bib0024">Huy and Anh., 2008</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, understanding forest structure and diversity, and carbon sink capacity is important (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0032" refid="bib0039">Malhi et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0004" view="all">The landscape approach to conservation and development adopted by Nepal since early 2000 has been successful in conserving biodiversity while also addressing the livelihood needs of local people. The Government has been implementing the landscape approach in coordination and partnership with key stakeholders and conservation organizations across the Terai Arc Landscape (TAL) (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0033" refid="bib0044">MoFSC, 2015</ce:cross-ref>). The TAL supports megafauna, such as tiger (<ce:italic>Panthera tigris</ce:italic>), elephant (<ce:italic>Elephas maximus</ce:italic>) and rhinoceros (<ce:italic>Rhinoceros unicornis</ce:italic>), by providing ecological connectivity through biological corridors that link protected areas. Because of its successful intervention in restoring critical habitats, the landscape has been recognized — and honored — as one of the seven UN World Restoration Flagships as part of the UN Decade on Ecosystem Restoration (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0034" refid="bib0069">UNEP, 2024</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0005" view="all">Our goal was to assess forest tree diversity and carbon stock in biological corridors and buffer zones within the Western TAL of Nepal. The biological corridors are recognized as critical areas linking different protected areas, which are managed by the community forest user groups as community forests, whereas buffer zones are integral parts of the protected areas but are managed by buffer zone user groups (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0035" refid="bib0043">MoFSC, 1996</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0036" refid="bib0042">MoFE, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). While forest products, including non-timber forest products, can be collected in sustainable ways in both systems according to operational plans, use of forest products in buffer zones is limited to fulfilling users’ needs but in community forests such products can be sold commercially as specified in the forest operational plans (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0037" refid="bib0042">MoFE, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Biological corridors are being managed under the Forest Act whereas buffer zones are declared and managed under the National Parks and Wildlife Conservation Act. Divisional Forest Offices are the responsible authorities for biological corridors whereas Park Managers have authority over buffer zones. Therefore, biological corridors and buffer zones represent two different management regimes. As forest inventories are always limited (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0038" refid="bib0067">Thurner et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>) and so is our understanding of tree diversity and forest carbon (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0039" refid="bib0048">Paquette and Messier, 2011</ce:cross-ref>), this study aimed to contribute to establishing a baseline for monitoring and management of the TAL of Nepal. Earlier studies have found that the spatial distribution of biomass and carbon stock is co-related to biodiversity (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0040" refid="bib0009">Cardinale et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0041" refid="bib0055">Ravenek et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>), soil health (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0042" refid="bib0045">Mueller et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>) and water regulation capacity (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0043" refid="bib0025">Ilstedt et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0044" refid="bib0071">Vanclay, 2009</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, this study will be important for planning and management of forest for multiple ecosystem services.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0002" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0005">Materials and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0003" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0006">Study area</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0006" view="all">The study was conducted in the Kamdi, Karnali, and Brahmadev biological corridors and the buffer zones of Banke and Bardia national parks (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0045" refid="fig0001">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0001"/>). Among seven corridors and forest conservation areas in TAL, the Brahmadev, Karnali and Kamdi corridors have critical ecological significance in connectivity maintenance and biodiversity conservation at the landscape level (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0046" refid="bib0044">MoFSC, 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Karnali is an extremely important corridor for preserving biodiversity in the region. It is located on the western edge of Bardia National Park and provides a pathway for tigers and elephants. The Brahmadev Corridor connects the Shuklaphanta National Park with Doon Forest in India, which borders the eastern bank of the Mahakali River and connects the Chure Forest in Nepal (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0047" refid="bib0066">Thapa and Tuladhar, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The Kamdi Corridor connects the Banke National Park in the north and the Sohelwa Wildlife Sanctuary of India in the south. These areas in western lowland Terai receive lower rainfall (total annual average 1700 mm) than other lowlands in the country (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0048" refid="bib0068">Timilsina et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>). The maximum temperature exceeds 40 °C in summer while the minimum temperature drops below 10 °C in winter. Forest fires, invasive species and past disturbances, including deforestation, are the major factors determining the structure and functions of these forests (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0049" refid="bib0068">Timilsina et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="crf0050" refid="bib0003">Bhatta et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>;; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0051" refid="bib0041">Mishra et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). The study sites were selected purposively because they were the least explored areas in terms of tree species diversity and carbon stock and also allowed us to compare various forest attributes in two different forest management regimes.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0004" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0007">Forest and vegetation types</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0007" view="all">Nine different forest and vegetation types are found in the study sites (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0052" refid="tbl0001">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0001"/>). Among the nine forest and vegetation types, <ce:italic>Shorea robusta</ce:italic> forests, Tropical mixed broad-leaved forests, and grasslands are found in all sites whereas <ce:italic>Pinus roxburghii-Shorea robusta</ce:italic> forest is found in the buffer zones of northern belt of Banke and Bardia National Parks. A few patches of <ce:italic>Pterocarpus marsupium</ce:italic> are also found in Brahmadev corridor.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0005" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0008">Sampling method</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0008" view="all">Concentric circular sample plots (CCSP) were established systematically on a 3 km by 3 km grid in all corridors and buffer zones to study tree species composition and estimate the above-ground biomass and carbon stock of the trees. The four circles of CCSP have different radii and diameter thresholds, all centered at the same point (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0053" refid="fig0002">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0002"/>). The outermost plot of radius of 20 m (r1, area=1256.6 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) was used for measuring the larger trees of diameter at breast height (DBH) equal to or greater than 30 cm, whereas r2 with radius of 15 m (area = 706.9 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) was used for measuring trees belonging to 20 cm to &lt;30 cm size classes, r3 with radius of 8 m (area = 201.1 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) was used for 10 cm to &lt;20 cm DBH and r4 with radius of 4 m (area= 50.3 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) was used for the trees with DBH from 5 to &lt;10 cm. This sampling design is consistent with the Forest Resource Assessment of Nepal (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0054" refid="bib0016">DFRS, 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0055" refid="bib0019">FRTC, 2019</ce:cross-ref>). A sample plot distribution map is presented in <ce:cross-ref id="crf0056" refid="fig0003">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0003"/>, which shows that a total of 94 clusters of CCSP were sampled: 27 in Banke National Park (NP) buffer zone (BZ), 33 in Bardia NP BZ, 11 each in Karnali and Brahmadev corridors and 12 in Kamdi Corridor. The number of CCSP corresponds to the area of the respective site. A diameter tape was used to measure DBH while a Suunto clinometer (accuracy of ± 0.5 m) was used to measure the height of all the trees inside these plots.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0006" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0009">Species identification</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0009" view="all">In cases where taxonomic identification of tree species in the field was certain, for example, <ce:italic>Pinus roxburghii</ce:italic> Sarg. and <ce:italic>Shorea robusta</ce:italic> Gaertn., herbarium specimens were not collected. For other species, photographs and field notes were taken and herbarium specimens were collected for further identification using standard literature (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0057" refid="bib0051">Polunin and Stainton, 1984</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0058" refid="bib0063">Stainton, 1984</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0059" refid="bib0062">Shrestha et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) and by comparing the herbarium specimens. The taxonomic treatment of plant families and species follows the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG) Classification 2016. The tree species in different botanical families were also identified for each plot.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0007" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0010">Species richness and diversity indices</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0010" view="all">The species richness as defined by <ce:cross-ref id="crf0060" refid="bib0072">Whittaker et al. (2001)</ce:cross-ref> was determined by counting the number of species in each plot. Shannon-Wiener and Simpson indices were used to calculate the species diversity (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0061" refid="bib0038">Magurran, 2004</ce:cross-ref>) while Pielou's Evenness index (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0062" refid="bib0050">Pielou, 1975</ce:cross-ref>) was used to calculate the evenness index.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0008" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0011">Data analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0011" view="all">Based on DBH measurement, the distribution of different size-class trees was grouped to examine the population structure. The volume of each tree was calculated according to the Forest Regulation 2022 (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0063" refid="bib0042">MoFE, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). The volume of different tree components — such as stem volume, branch volume and volume of the top 10 cm diameter — were added together to calculate the total volume. Below-ground biomass was estimated using the default value as recommended by the <ce:cross-ref id="crf0064" refid="bib0026">IPCC (2006)</ce:cross-ref>, which is one-fourth of the above-ground biomass. Species-specific wood density was obtained from the Global Wood Density database (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0065" refid="bib0073">Zanne et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>) and used to calculate the above-ground biomass of each tree. Estimating above-ground biomass follows the allometric equations by <ce:cross-ref id="crf0066" refid="bib0012">Chave et al. (2005)</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="para0012" view="all">Biomass and soil organic carbon are two major forest carbon pools (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0067" refid="bib0022">Gurung et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0068" refid="bib0018">FAO, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). In this study, living above-ground and below-ground biomass of trees and poles were calculated, expressed in tonnes of biomass per hectare, then converted into carbon multiplying by a carbon factor of 0.47 (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0069" refid="bib0026">IPCC, 2006</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="para0013" view="all">Statistical software package R was used to test the relationship between carbon stock and basal area, tree diversity, and tree density. The significance between number of species and families in different sites was tested using Chi-square (χ2) test. ArcMap and QGIS software were used to create geospatial maps indicating areas with different carbon stock classes in the study areas. Extrapolating carbon stock data resulted in different categories and that was divided into a maximum four classes for better presentation from lower to higher levels, also including the national average in between 145 and 200.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0009" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0012">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0010" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0013">Tree species diversity and stand characteristics at different study sites</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0014" view="all">Tree species inventories at the different study sites revealed the presence of the maximum number of species in the Bardia NP BZ while the least number of species were present in the Kamdi Corridor (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0070" refid="tbl0001">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). These species belonged to 19 taxonomic families in the Bardia NP BZ and the Brahmadev Corridor while the least number of taxonomic families were present in the Karnali Corridor. The χ2 test (χ2 = 0.507; df = 4; α = 0.05 and 1-α = 9.48) revealed that the number of species and families reported in different sites did not differ significantly. The Shannon-Weiner diversity index ranged 0.47–0.58 with the highest values in BZs whereas Simpson's diversity index was found to range 0.27–0.41 with the highest value in the biological corridors. Various vegetation characteristics of different study sites such as species richness, family richness, density, basal area, species diversity indices, and evenness index are presented in <ce:cross-ref id="crf0071" refid="tbl0002">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0002"/>.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0011" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0014">Tree density in different size classes</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0015" view="all">In terms of saplings (stems &lt;10 cm DBH), the highest numbers were reported from the Brahmadev Corridor (1166/ha) followed by the Bardia NP BZ (1154/ha). This accounts for 63–78 % of stems in Brahmadev Corridor and both buffer zones. The least number of saplings per hectare was reported from the Karnali Corridor followed by the Kamdi Corridor (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0072" refid="tbl0003">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0003"/>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="para0016" view="all">Overall, the highest number of stems per hectare was counted in the Brahmadev Corridor (<ce:italic>n</ce:italic> = 1848) followed by Bardia NP BZ (<ce:italic>n</ce:italic> = 1478). This pattern of stem count according to different DBH classes was different when saplings were separated. In this case, the highest number of stems per hectare was recorded from the Brahmadev Corridor followed by the Kamdi Corridor (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0073" refid="tbl0003">Table 3</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="crf0074" refid="fig0004">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0004"/>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="para0017" view="all">Likewise, the number of stems per hectare according to different DBH classes showed a pattern of reverse J-shape, meaning that the majority of the trees were found in smaller diameter classes (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0075" refid="fig0004">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0012" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0015">Biomass and carbon stock</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0018" view="all">Comparing the five different sites, the Brahmadev Corridor had the highest amount of carbon stock followed by Banke NP BZ. The lowest amount of carbon stock was measured for the Kamdi Corridor (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0076" refid="tbl0004">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0004"/>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="para0020" view="all">Trees in the highest DBH class (≥30) had the highest amount of carbon stock at all sites (minimum of 65 % to a maximum of 78 %) followed by pole-size trees, except in Bardia NP BZ where saplings had the second-highest amount of carbon stored (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0077" refid="tbl0005">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0005"/>). While considering tree species, the most dominant — <ce:italic>Shorea robusta</ce:italic> — had the highest amount of carbon (43.75–81.25 tons/ha) at all sites, except in Banke NP BZ where <ce:italic>Terminalia alata</ce:italic> Heyne ex Roth had the maximum amount of carbon (61.75 tons/ha). Except in Banke NP BZ, the co-dominant <ce:italic>Terminalia alata</ce:italic> had the highest amount of carbon stock. Other species contributing significant amounts of carbon stock were <ce:italic>Lagerstroemia parviflora</ce:italic> Roxb., <ce:italic>Anogeissus latifolia</ce:italic> (Roxb. Ex DC.) Wall. Ex Guill. &amp; Perr., and <ce:italic>Adina cordifolia</ce:italic> Benth. &amp; Hook. at all sites.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0013" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0016">High carbon stock forest areas</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0021" view="all">Forest areas with different carbon stock classes of the study sites are presented in <ce:cross-ref id="crf0078" refid="tbl0006">Table 6</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0006"/> and mapped in <ce:cross-ref id="crf0079" refid="fig0005">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0005"/>. This shows that the large proportion of forest areas in the Brahmadev Corridor (4507 ha) had a carbon stock class of 300–400 tons/ha followed by Bardia (1751 ha) and Banke NP (411 ha) BZs. There were no lower carbon stock forest classes (127–200 tons/ha) in the Brahmadev Corridor and no forest with the highest carbon stock class (300–400 tons/ha) in the Kamdi Corridor.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0014" view="all">
                     <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0017">Carbon stock and the relationship between different attributes</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="para0022" view="all">Carbon stock did not show significant variation with tree species richness, tree density, Shannon-Weiner diversity index, and Simpson diversity index (<ce:italic>p</ce:italic> &gt; 0.05). The basal area and the DBH showed a significant positive correlation, indicating a strong relationship between these variables (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0080" refid="tbl0007">Table 7</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0007"/>). Carbon stock in Bardia NP BZ was correlated with tree density while in Brahmadev Corridor it was correlated with the Simpson diversity index.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0015" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0018">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="para0023" view="all">Species diversity is the most commonly used measure of ecological diversity and can be assessed through species richness and diversity indices (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0081" refid="bib0021">Gonçalves et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0082" refid="bib0023">Hamilton, 2005</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0083" refid="bib0028">Izsák and Papp, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). Our vegetation analysis study at different sites representing two different management regimes revealed that biological corridors and park buffer zones had comparable tree species diversity. This might be due to conservation efforts in the biological corridors (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0084" refid="bib0044">MoFSC, 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Some of the biological corridors in Nepal have been given the status of forest conservation areas but these biological corridors are not recognized as such (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0085" refid="bib0066">Thapa and Tuladhar, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Nevertheless, these corridors are under community management that applies sustainable land management principles comprising methods and practices suitable for regional biophysical and socio-economic conditions aimed at the conservation, management, and sustainable use of resources (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0086" refid="bib0017">FAO, 2016</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0024" view="all">The comparatively higher values of the Shannon index and lower values of the Simpson index in buffer zones indicate higher diversity compared to the biological corridors. This could be because buffer zones have stricter regulations compared to biological corridors. However, from the diversity measures used, the overall species diversity values were below the expected values because young regrowth forests have normally high species diversity (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0087" refid="bib0021">Gonçalves et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0088" refid="bib0030">Kent and Coker, 1992</ce:cross-ref>). This might be due to severe disturbances in the past from anthropogenic activities at the study sites, which are some of the most fire-prone areas in Nepal (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0089" refid="bib0041">Mishra et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). An increase in fire frequency and severity alters the structure and composition of a forest, leading to plant diversity losses (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0090" refid="bib0007">Bowman et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0091" refid="bib0056">Richter et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Further, forests might have transformed into relatively uniform forests with high stem densities and limited species diversity, particularly, after community intervention (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0092" refid="bib0059">Sapkota et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0025" view="all">The density of trees in the Brahmadev Corridor was higher than that of the buffer zones but the lower density per hectare in the other two corridors reflects degraded conditions. The Brahmadev Corridor is important in maintaining ecological integrity and functioning in the Chure (Siwalik) hills of Nepal in the far west, one of the most vulnerable regions of Nepal (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0093" refid="bib0070">Uprety et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). The strong association between tree density, basal area, and carbon stock further signifies the effective management system in place by the community forest user groups. Comparing with national-level data, the stems per ha values (for poles and stems) are above the national average of 429.93/ha for all three corridors and below national average for both buffer zones (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0094" refid="bib0016">DFRS, 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Nonetheless, these values are below the average compared to similar vegetation zones in India (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0095" refid="bib0052">Pradhan et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0096" refid="bib0057">Sahu et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>). However, the study sites showed a basal area ranging 26–40 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>/ha, which is higher than the 13 m<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>/ha value obtained from similar sites in TAL (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0097" refid="bib0068">Timilsina et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>). The significant amount of stocking trees could have contributed to the relatively high basal area at the study sites. A significant relationship was observed between basal area and carbon stock at all sites, meaning that basal area is a key determinant of carbon stock (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0098" refid="bib0001">Balderas Torres and Lovett, 2013</ce:cross-ref>.)</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0026" view="all">A reverse J-shaped size class distribution of stems observed at the study sites indicates a stable population and good species recruitment. Furthermore, this inherent characteristic of natural forests is an important indication that serves as a basis for forest classification, biodiversity conservation and uneven-aged forest harvesting, which is important for resource utilization, including carbon management (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0099" refid="bib0013">Coomes and Allen, 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0100" refid="bib0029">Johnston and Withey, 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0101" refid="bib0033">Li et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0102" refid="bib0064">Sterba and Sterba, 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0027" view="all">The total biomass estimated in tree layers at the study sites (241.70–396.80 tons/ha) is within the range reported from similar sites in Nepal (<ce:cross-ref id="optlbSOxzryCY" refid="bib74">Thapa-Magar and Shrestha, 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0103" refid="bib0061">Shrestha et al., 2000</ce:cross-ref>) and India (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0104" refid="bib0011">Chaturvedi and Raghubanshi, 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0105" refid="bib0020">Gandhi and Sundarapandian, 2017</ce:cross-ref>) and higher than from comparable sites in Thailand (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0106" refid="bib0065">Terakunpisut et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>) and India (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0107" refid="bib0005">Bijalwan et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0108" refid="bib0006">Borah et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Compared to other studies, carbon stock at our study sites was higher than at other similar sites (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0109" refid="bib0006">Borah et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0110" refid="bib0052">Pradhan et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0111" refid="bib0058">Sahu et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>), with the pattern being sometimes below average from similar sites (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0112" refid="bib0002">Behera and Misra, 2006</ce:cross-ref>). A similar study by <ce:cross-ref id="crf0113" refid="bib0022">Gurung et al. (2015)</ce:cross-ref> in TAL estimated carbon stock at an average of 189.16 ± 26.46 Mg/ha, comparable with our study. Likewise, our findings are close to the national average of 176.95 tons/ha (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0114" refid="bib0016">DFRS, 2015</ce:cross-ref>) and higher than those from the core areas of the national park (154 tons/ha; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0115" refid="bib0004">Bhatta et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The management practices and disturbance factors significantly influenced the biomass and carbon stock at the study sites. The comparable carbon stock in both the buffer zones and the Brahmadev Corridor reflects the efforts of management authorities, whether through community forest user groups or buffer zone user groups. However, the Karnali and Kamdi Corridors displayed comparatively lower values of saplings in terms of number, stem volume, and their contribution to carbon stock. This can be attributed to various disturbances, such as encroachment, flooding, habitat degradation, uncontrolled forest fires, and intensive grazing, which pose major threats to these areas (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0116" refid="bib0044">MoFSC, 2015</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0117" refid="bib0066">Thapa and Tuladhar, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Additionally, these sites lack a long history of active management compared to others. Therefore, it is essential to address these threats to enhance carbon stock in the future.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="para0028" view="all">As the potential of forests to sequester carbon depends on the forest type, species diversity and dominance, age of forest, and size class of trees (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0118" refid="bib0065">Terakunpisut et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0119" refid="bib0060">Shang et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>), our disaggregated data of the size class of trees and mapping of areas with different carbon stock classes helps further understanding of the forests in critical corridors and buffer zones in western Nepal. Particularly, the data on the spatial distribution of carbon stock will be helpful for sustainable forest and watershed management, and carbon financing (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0120" refid="bib0035">Lin et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Furthermore, carbon-based policies based on information about current carbon stocks and possible changes are needed for the planners and policy makers in the context of climate change to manage human-dominated landscapes like TAL (<ce:cross-ref id="crf0121" refid="bib0015">Deere et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crf0122" refid="bib0049">Pechanec et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0016" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0019">Conclusion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="para0029" view="all">Our study focused on assessing the tree species diversity and carbon stock in tropical forests of the Western TAL of Nepal. The highest species richness was recorded in Bardia NP BZ and the lowest in Kamdi Corridor. The forests exhibited moderate species diversity. The carbon stock estimates (161.50 to 233.12 tons/ha) are comparable with many local, regional and national studies. The number of stems at all sites indicates a stable population and good species recruitment. Nevertheless, the lower number of stems in all classes in the Kamdi and Karnali corridors reflects degraded forest conditions. This suggests that these critical corridors require more management interventions. As other biological corridors in TAL are recognized as forest conservation areas, there is a need for similar management arrangements for these corridors. Our disaggregated data on the tree species diversity, size class distribution of trees, and mapping of areas with different carbon stocks provides important insights in planning and decision making into forest and carbon management, showing that areas with different carbon stocks need different management prescriptions.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0016a" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0019a">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="para0029a" view="all">
                     <ce:bold>Yadav Uprety:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Writing – original draft, Validation, Project administration, Methodology, Investigation, Funding acquisition, Formal analysis, Data curation, Conceptualization. <ce:bold>Bishwa Nath Oli:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Methodology, Funding acquisition, Conceptualization. <ce:bold>Sangram Karki:</ce:bold> Investigation, Formal analysis, Data curation. <ce:bold>Bijay Bashyal:</ce:bold> Investigation, Data curation. <ce:bold>Raj Kumar Rimal:</ce:bold> Methodology, Formal analysis. <ce:bold>Suman Subedi:</ce:bold> Project administration, Funding acquisition. <ce:bold>Bharat Gotame:</ce:bold> Project administration, Funding acquisition. <ce:bold>Sangeeta Rajbhandary:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Project administration, Funding acquisition. <ce:bold>Himlal Baral:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Funding acquisition, Formal analysis.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0001" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0021">Declaration of competing interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="para0031" view="all">Authors declare no competing interests</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0001" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="cesectitle0022">Acknowledgments</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="para0033" view="all">The field study received financial support from the <ce:grant-sponsor id="gs0002" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Integrated Landscape Management Project of the Ministry of Forests and Environment</ce:grant-sponsor>, WWF and GEF. We express our gratitude to Robert Finlayson from CIFOR-ICRAF for providing language editing. Article processing charge was supported by CIFOR-ICRAF.</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
         </body>
